#Text=Samuel Brooke

#Text=Dr Samuel Brooke ( 1575-1631 ) was a Gresham Professor of Divinity ( appointed 1612 ) , a playwright , the chaplain of Trinity College , Cambridge and subsequently the Master of Trinity ( 1629-1631 ) .
#Text=He was known to be an Arminian and anti- Calvinist .
#Text=In 1631 he was appointed archdeacon of Coventry .
#Text=Life
#Text=He was the son of Robert Brooke of York , the brother of Christopher Brooke who appears in George Wither 's eclogues under the pastoral name of Cuddie .
#Text=Samuel Brooke was educated at Westminster School and Trinity College , Cambridge , where he was admitted in 1596 ; he proceeded M.A. 1604 , B.D. 1607 , and D.D. 1615 . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=He was imprisoned for a short period , by the action of Sir George More , for secretly celebrating the marriage of John Donne with More 's daughter .

#Text=He was promoted to the office of chaplain to Henry Frederick , Prince of Wales , who recommended him ( 26 September 1612 ) as Gresham Professor of Divinity ; he was later chaplain to both James I and Charles I. [ 2 ]
#Text=On 13 June 1618 he became rector of St Margaret , Lothbury , London , and 10 July 1621 was incorporated D.D. at Oxford .

#Text=He was elected master of Trinity College , Cambridge , 5 September 1629 , and on 17 November resigned his Gresham professorship . On 13 May 1631 Brooke was admitted archdeacon of Coventry , and he died 16 September 1632 .
#Text=He was buried without monument or epitaph in Trinity College Chapel . [ 2 ]
#Text=Works
#Text=In 1614 he wrote three Latin plays , which were performed before James I on his visit to the university in that year .
#Text=The names of the plays were recorded as Scyros , Adelphe , and Melanthe . [ 2 ]
#Text=Adelphe derives from La Sorella by Giambattista della Porta . [ 3 ]

#Text=A central character in Melanthe is Nicander , the loutish heir of a rich father , who is laughed at and kicked around by the heroine Ermilla , before she finally decides to accept him as her husband . [ 4 ]
#Text=The play also contains a chorus of dancing satyrs . [ 5 ]
#Text=William Prynne in his Canterburie 's Doome attacked Brooke as a disciple of William Laud , and stated that in 1630 Brooke was engaged on Arminian treatise on predestination .
#Text=Laud encouraged him to complete this book , but afterwards declined to sanction its publication on account of a general prohibition on debating the subject . [ 6 ]
#Text=None of Brooke 's works were printed .

#Text=Besides the treatise already mentioned , a manuscript of the first three books of which is in Trinity College Library , he wrote a tract on the Thirty-nine Articles , and a discourse , dedicated to the Earl of Pembroke , entitled De Auxilio Divinæ Gratiæ Exercitatio theologica , nimirum : An possibile sit duos eandem habere Gratiæ Mensuram , et tamen unus convertatur et credat ; alter non : e Johan . xi . 45 , 46 . [ 2 ]
#Text=The manuscript of this is in the Cambridge University Library .
#Text=Manuscripts
#Text=Trinity College , Cambridge , MS B. 15 . 13 .
#Text=' De Natura & Ordine divinæ Prædestinationis in Ecclesiâ , vel intra Ecclesiam Dei . ' [ 7 ]
#Text=Cambridge University Library , MS Additional 44 , item 16 .
#Text=' De Auxilio Divinæ Gratiæ Exercitatio theologica . ' [ 8 ]
